To find numbers that do not have paired/odd neighbors in a 3x3 matrix in JavaScript, you can use the following code:

```javascript
let matrix = [[1,2,3],[4,5,6],[7,8,9]];
let result = [];

for(let i=0; i matrix.length; i++){
    for(let j=0; jmatrix[i].length; j++){
        let current = matrix[i][j];
        let neighbors = [];
        if(i   0){
            neighbors.push(matrix[i-1][j]);
        }
        if(i   matrix.length-1){
            neighbors.push(matrix[i+1][j]);
        }
        if(j   0){
            neighbors.push(matrix[i][j-1]);
        }
        if(j   matrix[i].length-1){
            neighbors.push(matrix[i][j+1]);
        }
        let oddNeighbors = neighbors.filter(n =  n%2 !== 0);
        let pairedNeighbors = neighbors.filter(n => n%2 === 0);
        if(oddNeighbors.length === 0 || pairedNeighbors.length === 0){
            result.push(current);
        }
    }
}

console.log(result);
```

This code creates a 3x3 matrix and then loops through each element of the matrix. For each element, it checks its four neighbors (up, down, left, and right) and determines whether they are odd or even. If there are no odd or even neighbors (i.e., all neighbors are either odd or even), then the current element is added to the result array.

You can replace the values in the `matrix` array with your own values.

